Landan and his wife once depended only on the harvesting of palm oil to make a living.
.
Today, thanks to your searches, our partners can support families like his in creating alternative livelihoods. For example, harvesting the Tenkawang tree.
Unlike the palm oil producing tree, this one only grows in diverse forests and doesn‚Äôt thrive in monocultures, which are damaging to the soil. This tree also produces a nut known as ‚Äúgreen butter‚Äù because of the texture of its oil ‚Äì which can be used for cooking, cosmetics or biofuel.
.
During the harvesting time, Landan and his wife collect as many nuts as possible. One part of the nuts is cooked, the other one is sun-dried to produce the oil and butter that they can also sell in local and international markets.
.
Tenkawang trees can only be harvested once every couple of years. So they‚Äôre not as efficient as palm oil-producing trees. But they form part of a larger solution that helps to benefit people and nature. .
That‚Äôs why your searches help us to plant them in Indonesia, along other (fruit) trees. In combination, they are helping farmers like Landan restore their degraded lands, turning them into thriving forest gardens which they can live off. üå≥‚úäüèΩüíö
